  <div id="grooming" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Grooming: Silk, Kept Sensible in the Tropics" imageAlt="Havanese puppy having its silky coat combed through" imageSrc={imgScene3} imagePosition="left">
      <p>Overseas Havanese guides describe full-length show coats and corded styles, and you can ignore all of it: in Singapore's humidity the sensible Havanese lives in a puppy cut. That brings the routine to a brush 2 to 3 times a week with a weekly comb-through to the skin, a salon trim every 4 to 6 weeks, and quick drying after rainy walks; the lightweight coat dries faster than it looks like it should.</p>
      <p>The daily ten-second habit is an eye-area wipe on cream and light-gold faces to stay ahead of tear staining. Everything you need to start is in your kit, and we show you the routine on delivery day.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>

  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" />
  <div id="health" class="scroll-mt-40">
    <CaptionedBlock heading="Havanese Health: What We Check Before You Take One Home" imageAlt="Havanese puppy at a veterinary health check before going home" imageSrc={imgScene4} variant="mid">
      <p>Every Havanese goes home vet-checked, vaccinated, dewormed, and microchipped. Health is one of this breed's best stories: the Havanese is robust and long-lived, which the 13-to-16-year expectancy reflects. The short watch-list: patellar luxation, the small-breed kneecap issue; eye checks, sensible in any toy breed line; and dental care in a small jaw, met with the day-one brushing habit.</p>
      <p>Feeding is simple: your puppy comes with the food it is already eating, and any change should be gradual over a week. For portioning guidance see the <a href="/learn/puppy-health" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">puppy health checks explained</a> guide.</p>
    </CaptionedBlock>
  </div>
  <CloudDivider fillClass="fill-[var(--color-mint-100)]" flip />

  <CaptionedBlock heading="Your Havanese's First Week at Home" imageAlt="Havanese puppy settling into a set-up playpen during its first week home" imageSrc={imgScene5} imagePosition="left">
    <p>Day 0: we deliver, free, at a time that suits you, usually morning or evening. The playpen, bed, water, and toys are set up before your Havanese explores the room, and we walk you through all 30+ starter-kit items in person. Learn more about <a href="/delivery" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">how our free home delivery and setup works</a>.</p>
    <p>Days 1 to 3: keep it calm and close. This breed settles through proximity: the playpen where it can see people, a fixed feeding routine, and the toilet pads where we placed them. Some night whimpering is normal adjustment.</p>
    <p>Days 4 to 7: the routine sticks, and two habits start now while they're easy: book your free first lesson with an AVS-certified trainer, and practise short, boring departures, five minutes at a time, because a velcro breed's alone-time skills are built early or not at all. See <a href="/free-training" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">what the free AVS-certified training lesson covers</a>.</p>
  </CaptionedBlock>

  <div id="reviews" class="scroll-mt-40">
